AGI - There are 800 thousand people forced to flee from Rafah, because of the Israeli military operation in the city in the south of the Palestinian enclave. "It's 80,000 people who set themselves in motion, forced to flee, since the Israeli forces started military operation in the area on May 6," denounced the head of the Unrwa, the agency for Palestinian refugees, Philippe Lazzarini on X.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Raid on refugee camp Nusseirat</h2>
An Israeli air raid killed 20 people before sunrise in the Nusseirat refugee camp in the Gaza Strip. It was reported by medical sources of the Al-Aqsa hospital.<br> "We received 20 deaths and several injuries after an Israeli air strike targeted a house that belonged to the Hassan family in the Nusseirat camp," said the Al-Aqsa hospital.<br> According to other witnesses, the attack occurred in the middle of the night, around 3:00 in the morning. The Israeli army has announced that it wants to verify the incident.&nbsp;
<h2>Gantz: "Piano for the future of Gaza or I dimetto"</h2>
Meanwhile, Israeli war minister Benny Gantz announced that he will resign from the government if Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will not give way to a post-war plan for the Gaza Strip.<br> "The war cabinet must formulate and approve by 8 June an action plan that will lead to the realization of six strategic objectives of national importance or we will be forced to resign from the government," Gantz said, referring to his party, in a television speech directed at Netanyahu. Gantz said that the six goals include: the overthrow of Hamas, ensure Israeli security control over the Palestinian territory and return Israeli hostages. "As well as maintaining Israeli security control, establishing an American, European, Arab and Palestinian administration that will manage civil affairs in the Gaza Strip and laying the ground for a future alternative that is not Hamas or Mahmoud Abbas," he said, referring to the President of the Palestinian Authority. He also urged the normalization of links with Saudi Arabia "as part of a global move that will create an alliance with the free world and the Arab world against Iran and its affiliates
<h2> The replica of &nbsp;Netanyahu</h2>
Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu immediately replied accusing Gantz of "launching an ultimatum to the prime minister instead of launching an ultimatum to Hamas". Netanyahu's office states in a statement that Gantz's demands would mean "the end of war and defeat for Israel, the abandonment of most hostages, the permanence of Hamas in power and the creation of a Palestinian State".
1) Does Gantz want the operation to Rafah to come to the end and, if yes, why threatens to overthrow the national unit government during the IDF operation? ;
2) Does he oppose the Palestinian Authority government in Gaza, even though Mahmoud Abbas is not involved? ;
3) Would it support a Palestinian state as part of a standardization process with Saudi Arabia?" <br> "Prime Netanyahu is determined to eliminate Hamas battalions," says Netanyahu's office, "is opposed to the introduction of the Palestinian Authority in Gaza and the creation of a Palestinian State that will inevitably be a terrorist state." Netanyahu - the communiqué continues - believes that the government of national unity is fundamental to achieve the objectives of the war, "and expects Gantz to make clear to the public its positions on these issues"
<h2>Sullivan at Riad, meets Crown Prince MbS</h2>
White House National Security Counselor Jake Sullivan is in Riad where he met Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman. The two, reports the Saudi agency, discussed a broad-range bilateral agreement and the Israeli war against Hamas in Gaza. After his visit to Saudi Arabia, Sullivan will fly to Israel, where he will meet Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu to update him on his talks at Riad and discuss the planned Israeli military operation in Rafah.
&nbsp;

